<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-917-304  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 917 304.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  Oct 19 1989 n1186 p28(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The image of efficient design. (British Petroleum uses a documentimaging system to create and modify blueprints)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Vowler, Julia.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>British Petroleum (BP) used a computer system with a scanner toupdate blueprints on construction of an oil platform in the NorthSea.andP;  Oil platforms are complex structures to build, and ensuringthat workers have up-to-date blueprints is difficult.andP;  The NorthSea project used 35,000 drawings which, despite the cost, BPdecided to digitize using a 750,000-pounds-sterling SpectrumDatagraphics Systems scanning and management system.andP;  The companyused the Ingres database management system for the front end.andP;  BPscanned 17,000 drawings in four weeks using two scanners 16 hourseach day.andP;  The drawings then could be easily modified and the manyrevisions cataloged.andP;  Documents are kept on 800Mbyte and opticaldisks, and BP backs up each night.andP;  Now the project team can see adrawing's pending changes, the current status and revisionhistory.andP;  The system is also useful for remote sites to accessdata.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   British Petroleum Company PLC (automation).andO;Ticker:    BP.andO;Topic:     Oil IndustryComputer-Aided DesignScanningCase StudyConstruction Industry.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>